<span class="PRTitle"><!-- NewsTitle.start -->Establishment of National High Schools approved by the Senate<!-- NewsTitle.end --></span>
</p>
<!-- NewsBody.start --><p style="text-align: justify">The Senate today passed on third and final reading 90 bills establishing national high schools.            Senate Education, Arts and Culture Committee Chairman Edgardo Angara sponsored all 90 House bills together with Senate Finance Committee Chairman Franklin Drilon.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify">The 90 House bills approved were for the establishment of National High Schools. The 14 remaining House bills called for the renaming State Universities and Colleges.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify">Angara pointed out that the importance of the establishment of National High Schools is vital to the implementation of the K to 12 program of the Deparment of Education (DepEd).</p>
<p style="text-align: justify">The 90 National High Schools shall be located in San Fernando, Cebu, Carcar, Cebu, Antipolo, Rizal, Quezon, Nueva Vizcaya, Calidngan Carcar, Cebu, Tuyom Carcar, Cebu, Tabuk, Kalinga, Valencia, Bukidnon, Malaybalay, Bukidnon, Kalasungay Malaybalay, Bukidnon, Casisang Malaybalay, Bukidnon, Catumbalon Valencia, Bukidnon, Laoag, Ilocos Norte, Talisay, Negros Occidental, Pamplona, Camarines Sur, Pinukpuk, Kalinga, Tongantongan Valencia, Bukidnon, Naga, Cebu, Concepcion Valencia, Bukidnon, Carcar, Cebu, Tabuk, Kalinga, Pasig, Metro Manila, San Pablo, Laguna, Maria Aurora, Aurora, Surigao, Surigao Del Norte, Cantilan, Surigao Del Sur, Maasin, Southern Leyte, Malolos, Bulacan, Looc, Romblon, Iligan, Lanao Del Norte, Ditucalan Iligan, Lanao Del Norte, Kiwalan Iligan, Lanao Del Norte, Aglayan Malaybalay, Bukidnon, San Pablo, Zamboanga Del Sur, Tabina, Zamboanga Del Sur, Kumalarang, Zamboanga Del Sur, Guipos, Zamboanga Del Sur, Danao, Cebu, Tukuran, Zamboanga Del Sur, Burgos, La Union, Pantukan, Compostela Valley, Libmanan, Camarines Sur, Bunawan District, Davao, Nabunturan, Compostela Valley, Laak, Compostela Valley, Canumay, Valenzuela, Sta, Maria, Bulacan, Linapacan, Palawan, Batangas, Batangas, Bacolod, Negros Occidental, Lanas Naga, Cebu, Calavera Naga, Cebu, Cabuan Naga, Cebu, Tagbilaran, Bohol, Pikit, North Cotabato, Dalandag Pikit, North Cotabato, Midsayap, North Cotabato, Navotas, Metro Manila, Hinatuan, Surigao Del Sur, Mayana Naga, Cebu, Mainit Naga, Cebu, Minglanilla, Cebu, Gingoog, Misamis Oriental, Binakalan Gingoog, Misamis Oriental, Kalipay Gingoog, Misamis Oriental, Balong Tabuk, Kalinga,  Asibanglan, Pinukpuk, Kalinga, Calapan, Oriental Mindoro, Hinaplanon, Iligan, Lanao Del Norte, Kabacsanan, Iligan, Lanao Del Norte, Daanbantayan, Cebu, Paypay, Daanbantayan, Cebu, San Agustin, Romblon, Magdiwang, Romblon, Tanudan, Kalinga, Itogon, Benguet, Pasil, Kalinga, Compostela, Compostela Valley, Balatoc, Pasil, Kalinga, Baguio, Baguio City, Aurora Hill, Baguio, Baguio City, Happy Hollow, Baguio, Baguio City, Lindawan, Baguio, Baguio City, Quezon Hill, Baguio City, Pinget, Baguio, Asipulo, Ifugao, Dominican- Mirador, Baguio City, Bakakeng, Baguio City, Pacdal, Baguio City, and San Vicente, Baguio City.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify">Meanwhile, the Senate also approved on third and final reading Senate Bill No. 3276, an Act declaring the first week of February every year as "World Interfaith Harmony Week", seeks to promote mutual understanding and inter-religious dialogue among leaders and representatives of religious and secular organizations.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify">The United Nations General Assembly (UN GA) proclaimed in October 20, 2010 the first week of February of every year as the "World Interfaith Harmony Week between all religions, faiths and beliefs," through resolution A/RES/65/5.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify">"The rationale of the UN resolution is a need to find genuine understanding among people of different faiths and belief systems. This finds resonance in the Philippines, a country that will certainly benefit from dialogues among leaders and representatives of religious institutions. The harmony we are pushing for is democratic, and built on effective communication and mutual respect," Sen. Loren Legarda said.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify">Senate Bill No. 3276 seeks to promote cooperation and genuine understanding among all Filipinos, in order to establish a country of empathy and a culture of peace.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify">"It is in the best interests of the Filipino people to promote civil and non-violent inter-religious and inter-cultural dialogues. These dialogues will empower our democratic ideals and engender an environment conducive to the prosperity of all," Legarda said.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify">"Since time immemorial, lives and civilizations have been the pawns of wars and conflicts fought in the name of religion. Right here in the Philippines, we have our own share of armed conflict and violence between Christians and Muslims. Our challenge and our goal is to build a sense of community that goes beyond the traditional boundaries of clan, tribe, class, region, and religion. I believe that mutual understanding and cooperation will help us achieve a united nation," Angara said in his sponsorship speech.</p>
